Originally, too, they continued in office forfive years. Subse- quently, however, an election of censors took place at the end of every five years, but those who were elected held their power for only eighteen months. At first their power was but small, but eventually became very great. All orders of the State were subject to them. They estimated the fortunes of citizens; divided them into classes and centuries; enquired into their morals; could inflict marks of disgrace, by removing from a higher to a lower rank, and could expel senators from tho Senate.
